    "answers": [
        {
            "owner": {
                "profile_image": "https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/cef1e86177cbf2c293b59ac56492e3c7?s=256&d=identicon&r=PG",
                "account_id": 101585,
                "user_type": "registered",
                "user_id": 273200,
                "link": "https://stackoverflow.com/users/273200/bala-r",
                "reputation": 109373,
                "display_name": "Bala R",
                "accept_rate": 100
            },
            "content_license": "CC BY-SA 4.0",
            "score": 66,
            "is_accepted": true,
            "last_activity_date": 1535747760,
            "creation_date": 1324563475,
            "body": "<pre><code>public class Foo {\n    static {\n         System.out.println(\"Message\");\n         System.exit(0);\n    } \n}\n<\/code><\/pre>\n\n<p>The <code>System.exit(0)<\/code> exits program before the jvm starts to look for <code>main()<\/code><\/p>\n\n<p><sub>(Note: This works only with java 6. Even if it compiles with JDK 7's <code>javac<\/code> it cannot be run with its <code>java<\/code>, because it expects a <code>main(String[])<\/code> method.)<\/sub><\/p>\n",
            "answer_id": 8605155,
            "question_id": 8605137,
            "last_edit_date": 1535747760
        },
        {
            "owner": {
                "profile_image": "https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/bad8fc8c24f4fa4c84ad436f2bdf4270?s=256&d=identicon&r=PG",
                "account_id": 1028420,
                "user_type": "registered",
                "user_id": 1037210,
                "link": "https://stackoverflow.com/users/1037210/lion",
                "reputation": 19087,
                "display_name": "Lion",
                "accept_rate": 100
            },
            "content_license": "CC BY-SA 3.0",
            "score": 12,
            "is_accepted": false,
            "last_activity_date": 1406797018,
            "creation_date": 1324735578,
            "body": "<pre><code>public final class Main {\n    static {\n        System.out.println(\"Hello World\");\n        System.exit(0);\n    }\n}\n<\/code><\/pre>\n\n<p>The static block is first executed as soon as the class is loaded before the <code>main();<\/code> method is invoked and therefore before <code>main()<\/code> is called, <code>System.exit(0)<\/code> initiates VM shut down.<\/p>\n\n<p><strong>The <code>System.exit<\/code> method halts the execution of the current thread and all others dead in their tracks.<\/strong> When <code>System.exit<\/code> is called, the virtual machine performs two cleanup tasks before shutting down. <\/p>\n\n<p>First, it executes all shutdown hooks that have been registered with<code>Runtime.addShutdownHook<\/code>. This is useful to release resources external to the VM. Use shutdown hooks for behavior that must occur before the VM exits.<\/p>\n\n<p>The second cleanup task performed by the VM when <code>System.exit<\/code> is called\nconcerns finalizers. If either <code>System.runFinalizersOnExit<\/code> or its evil twin\n<code>Runtime.runFinalizersOnExit<\/code> has been called, the VM runs the finalizers on\nall objects that have not yet been finalized. These methods were deprecated a long\ntime ago and with good reason. Never call <code>System.runFinalizersOnExit<\/code> or\n<code>Runtime.runFinalizersOnExit<\/code> for any reason: They are among the most\ndangerous methods in the Java libraries. Calling these methods can result in finalizers being run on live objects while other threads are concurrently manipulating\nthem, resulting in erratic behavior or deadlock.<\/p>\n\n<p>In summary, <code>System.exit<\/code> stops all program threads immediately; it does not\ncause finally blocks to execute, but it does run shutdown hooks before halting\nthe VM. Use shutdown hooks to terminate external resources when the VM shuts\ndown. It is possible to halt the VM without executing shutdown hooks by calling\n<code>System.halt<\/code>, but this method is rarely used.<\/p>\n",
            "answer_id": 8624991,
            "question_id": 8605137,
            "last_edit_date": 1406797018
        },
        {
            "owner": {
                "profile_image": "https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/53ee9941b3fefef67175daf212e62d41?s=256&d=identicon&r=PG",
                "account_id": 23121,
                "user_type": "registered",
                "user_id": 57695,
                "link": "https://stackoverflow.com/users/57695/peter-lawrey",
                "reputation": 535107,
                "display_name": "Peter Lawrey",
                "accept_rate": 75
            },
            "content_license": "CC BY-SA 3.0",
            "score": 11,
            "is_accepted": false,
            "last_activity_date": 1324563786,
            "creation_date": 1324563786,
            "body": "<p>In a file called <code>A.java<\/code><\/p>\n\n<pre><code>class Con {\n    String hi = \"\\n\\nHello World\\n\\n\";\n}\n<\/code><\/pre>\n\n<p>You just have to compile the program on Windows. Not run it. :-P<\/p>\n",
            "answer_id": 8605207,
            "question_id": 8605137
        },
        {
            "owner": {
                "profile_image": "https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/0b95808f862420ae7f6305fcb206299e?s=256&d=identicon&r=PG",
                "account_id": 1077525,
                "user_type": "registered",
                "user_id": 1075341,
                "link": "https://stackoverflow.com/users/1075341/arnaud",
                "reputation": 7489,
                "display_name": "Arnaud",
                "accept_rate": 96
            },
            "content_license": "CC BY-SA 3.0",
            "score": 8,
            "is_accepted": false,
            "last_activity_date": 1377768020,
            "creation_date": 1377768020,
            "body": "<p>You could define a custom class loader that prints your message :<\/p>\n\n<pre><code>public class MyClassLoader extends ClassLoader {\n    public MyClassLoader(ClassLoader other) {\n         super(other);\n         System.out.println(\"Hi there\");\n         System.exit(0);\n    }\n}\n<\/code><\/pre>\n\n<p>Then run the java command :<\/p>\n\n<p><code>java -Djava.system.class.loader=MyClassLoader<\/code><\/p>\n\n<p>(don't need to add a class as parameter)<\/p>\n",
            "answer_id": 18506906,
            "question_id": 8605137
        },
        {
            "owner": {
                "profile_image": "https://i.sstatic.net/pD7bn.jpg?s=256",
                "account_id": 230229,
                "user_type": "registered",
                "user_id": 493707,
                "link": "https://stackoverflow.com/users/493707/massimiliano-peluso",
                "reputation": 26827,
                "display_name": "Massimiliano Peluso",
                "accept_rate": 64
            },
            "content_license": "CC BY-SA 3.0",
            "score": 6,
            "is_accepted": false,
            "last_activity_date": 1324575921,
            "creation_date": 1324563917,
            "body": "<pre><code>class MainMethodNot\n{\n    static\n    {\n        System.out.println(\"Hello World\");\n        System.exit(0);\n\n    }\n}\n<\/code><\/pre>\n\n<p>Because the static initializer block is executed when the class is first loaded, we can print out \u201cHello World\u201d without writing a main method. The execution is stopped using \u201cSystem.exit()\u201d command. So, we prevent \u201cmain method not found\u201d error. \nIt's quite a tricky question<\/p>\n",
            "answer_id": 8605226,
            "question_id": 8605137,
            "last_edit_date": 1324575921
        },
        {
            "owner": {
                "profile_image": "https://i.sstatic.net/zkGuf.jpg?s=256",
                "account_id": 2516239,
                "user_type": "registered",
                "user_id": 2187621,
                "link": "https://stackoverflow.com/users/2187621/pankaj-manali",
                "reputation": 708,
                "display_name": "Pankaj Manali",
                "accept_rate": 60
            },
            "content_license": "CC BY-SA 3.0",
            "score": 3,
            "is_accepted": false,
            "last_activity_date": 1425213077,
            "creation_date": 1425213077,
            "body": "<p>It was possible till java 6 to use System.out.println(); without main().\nFrom java 7 onwards, it is not possible to do it with static block. It will still ask for main method in main class.<\/p>\n",
            "answer_id": 28793550,
            "question_id": 8605137
        },
        {
            "owner": {
                "profile_image": "https://i.sstatic.net/fUOFo.png?s=256",
                "account_id": 3673238,
                "user_type": "registered",
                "user_id": 3059893,
                "link": "https://stackoverflow.com/users/3059893/javahopper",
                "reputation": 5607,
                "display_name": "JavaHopper",
                "accept_rate": 45
            },
            "content_license": "CC BY-SA 3.0",
            "score": 2,
            "is_accepted": false,
            "last_activity_date": 1461518635,
            "creation_date": 1461518635,
            "body": "<p>If you don't want to use static block too, it can be done following way<\/p>\n\n<pre><code>public class NoMain {\n\n    private static final int STATUS = getStatus();\n\n    private static int getStatus() {\n        System.out.println(\"Hello World!!\");\n        System.exit(0);\n        return 0;\n    }\n\n}\n<\/code><\/pre>\n\n<p>However, please note that this is for Java 6 version. Its <a href=\"https://stackoverflow.com/questions/35699087/why-java-7-version-does-not-support-to-run-program-without-main-method?lq=1\">not working in Java 7<\/a> which is said to be supported in Java 8. I tried with JDK 1.8.0_77-b03, which is still not working<\/p>\n",
            "answer_id": 36826494,
            "question_id": 8605137,
            "last_edit_date": 1495542870
        },
        {
            "owner": {
                "profile_image": "https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/c7d2089e6fbf23826af0f9da82ad9088?s=256&d=identicon&r=PG",
                "account_id": 1409981,
                "user_type": "registered",
                "user_id": 1336793,
                "link": "https://stackoverflow.com/users/1336793/sunny",
                "reputation": 1955,
                "display_name": "sunny",
                "accept_rate": 44
            },
            "content_license": "CC BY-SA 3.0",
            "score": 2,
            "is_accepted": false,
            "last_activity_date": 1503435154,
            "creation_date": 1503435154,
            "body": "<p>Yes, you can print a message to console without using main().<\/p>\n\n<p>Create a test with JUnit and execute it:<\/p>\n\n<pre><code>@Test\npublic printTest()   {\n   System.out.println(\"myprint\");\n}\n<\/code><\/pre>\n",
            "answer_id": 45826773,
            "question_id": 8605137
        },
        {
            "owner": {
                "profile_image": "https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/5144f0d486f7a675de0a4ba70295e26a?s=256&d=identicon&r=PG&f=y&so-version=2",
                "account_id": 4777922,
                "user_type": "registered",
                "user_id": 3860537,
                "link": "https://stackoverflow.com/users/3860537/niranjan",
                "reputation": 1909,
                "display_name": "Niranjan",
                "accept_rate": 33
            },
            "content_license": "CC BY-SA 3.0",
            "score": 1,
            "is_accepted": false,
            "last_activity_date": 1414996448,
            "creation_date": 1414996086,
            "body": "<p>Yes, one of the way is static block but in previous version of JDK not in JDK 1.7.<\/p>\n\n<pre><code>class Withoutmain{  \n static{  \n  System.out.println(\"Message: Your message can be print on console without main() method\");  \n  System.exit(0);  \n }  \n}  \n<\/code><\/pre>\n\n<p>Output:Message: Your message can be print on console without main() method (if not JDK7)<\/p>\n\n<p>Output:Error: Main method not found in class A3, please define the main method as:\npublic static void main(String[] args)<\/p>\n\n<p><a href=\"http://www.javatpoint.com/static-keyword-in-java#staticwithoutmain\" rel=\"nofollow\">Reference<\/a><\/p>\n",
            "answer_id": 26708908,
            "question_id": 8605137,
            "last_edit_date": 1414996448
        },
        {
            "owner": {
                "profile_image": "https://i.sstatic.net/Cma0X.jpg?s=256",
                "account_id": 9281755,
                "user_type": "registered",
                "user_id": 6892765,
                "link": "https://stackoverflow.com/users/6892765/anurag0510",
                "reputation": 763,
